messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

- Full HTTP request path:
  /consumer/notifications

- All HTTP methods acceptable: false

- HEAD: false
- POST: false
- OPTIONS: false
- TRACE: false
- GET: true
- PUT: false
- DELETE: false
- PATCH: false

Explanation:
- The method getConsumerNotifications is annotated with @RequestMapping(value = "/consumer/notifications", method = RequestMethod.GET), so the explicit mapped path is "/consumer/notifications" and the explicit HTTP method is GET.
- There is no class-level @RequestMapping in NotificationsController, so no additional prefix is present in this source file.
- Because the mapping explicitly declares RequestMethod.GET, only GET is accepted according to the source code. I marked other methods (POST, PUT, DELETE, PATCH, OPTIONS, TRACE, HEAD) as false because they are not declared in the @RequestMapping for this handler.
- Note: Spring MVC can implicitly support HEAD for GET handlers at runtime, but per your instruction I decided acceptance based solely on the code annotations (no implicit/runtime behavior), so HEAD is reported as false.
- The handler is also protected by @Secured({"ROLE_USER"}) (in the source), and it returns List<Notification> using the Principal to determine the current consumer.
